05609nam a22008055i 9780228015673DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280156737 a10.1515/97802280156732doi  a(DE-B1597)658122  a(OCoLC)1353604892  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1059.5.T688bA33 2023 7aARC0240002bisacsh04a728.809713/54122300aCasa Loma :bMillionaires, Medievalism, and Modernity in Toronto’s Gilded Age /ced. by Matthew M. Reeve, Michael Windover. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b150 illustrations, duotone  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History ;v4200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCasa Loma, Sir Henry Pellatt, and the City of Toronto -- tHouses on the Ridge -- tCasa Loma’s Architect -- tThe Design and Construction of Casa Loma, 1905–1913 -- tThe Casa Loma Collections and the Sale of 1924 -- tPerforming Place -- tA Modern Castle -- t“Pellatt’s Folly” -- t“Toronto’s White Elephant” and “Canada’s Famous Castle” -- tCasa Loma, 1970 to the Present -- tFigures -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLeading architect E.J. Lennox designed Casa Loma for the flamboyant Sir Henry Pellatt and Mary, Lady Pellatt as an enormous castellated mansion that overlooked the booming metropolis of Toronto. The first scholarly book dedicated to this Canadian landmark, Casa Loma situates the famous “house on the hill” within Toronto’s architectural, urban, and cultural history.Casa Loma was not only an outsized home for the self-appointed “Lord Toronto” but a statement of Canada’s association with empire, an assertion of the country’s British legacy. During and after the Pellatts’ occupation, Casa Loma was a major landmark, and it has since infiltrated the iconography and collective memory of the metropolis. The reception of Casa Loma, variously loved and abhorred by Torontonians, reflects many of Toronto’s major aspirations and anxieties about itself as a modern city. Across ten chapters, this book charts the history of Casa Loma from the purchase of the estate atop Davenport Ridge in 1903 and its construction from 1906, through to its sale and the dispersal of its contents in 1924, its subsequent life as a hotel, and finally its transformation into one of the city’s major entertainment venues.Casa Loma brings to light a wealth of hitherto unpublished archival images and documentation of the house’s visual and material culture, weaving together a textured account of the design, use, and life of this unique building over the course of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchitecture, DomesticzOntariozTorontoxHistory. 0aHistoric buildingszOntariozToronto. 0aMansionszOntariozTorontoxHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / Buildings / General.2bisacsh  aCastle.  aEJ Lennox.  aEdwardian.  aHenry Pellatt.  aantiques.  aart.  acollections.  aimperialism.  amodern.  anationalism.  apress.  aradio.  atourism.1 aBlank, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoutu, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReeve, Matthew M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReeve, Matthew M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTorres, Marcela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVattay, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWindover, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.